  ],
  "snippets": [
    {
      "text": "3-iodothyronamine (T(1)AM) is a novel endogenous relative of thyroid hormone, able to interact with trace amine-associated receptors, a class of plasma membrane G protein-coupled receptors, and to produce a negative inotropic and chronotropic effect",
      "document": "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19298522",
      "beginSection": "sections.0",
      "endSection": "sections.0"
    },
    {
      "text": "In adult rat cardiomyocytes acute exposure to 20 microM T(1)AM decreased the amplitude and duration of the calcium transient.",
      "document": "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19298522",
      "beginSection": "sections.0",
      "endSection": "sections.0"
    },
    {
      "text": "In normal porcine myocardium T3 had no effect on the extent of isometric force generation but accelerated the time course of force development (p < 0.05) and increased the calcium transient (p < 0.001). After induction of myocardial depression by epinephrine exposure T3 accelerated the intracellular calcium transients and reduced diastolic calcium",
      "document": "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9875761",
      "beginSection": "sections.0",
      "endSection": "sections.0"
    },
    {
      "text": "The experimental data showing increased force amplitudes at unaltered amplitudes of the intracellular calcium transient and an even-reduced calcium time integral provide strong evidence for a sensitization of the contractile apparatus for calcium by triiodothyronine",
      "document": "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9773867",
      "beginSection": "sections.0",
      "endSection": "sections.0"
    },
    {
      "text": "hese results indicate that the thyroid state influences the time course of the calcium transient and are consistent with the abbreviation in the duration of contraction that is observed in the hyperthyroid state.",
      "document": "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2428004",
      "beginSection": "sections.0",
      "endSection": "sections.0"
    }
